WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.280
Welcome, everybody, to the next installment of Chemistry to the Clinic.

2
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:07.390
This is part two of four, Beyond Inhibition: The Next

3
00:00:07.400 --> 00:00:09.680
Frontier in Proximity Inducing Therapies.

4
00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:15.080
I'm Michael Erb. I'm a chemical biologist in the Department of Chemistry at the

5
00:00:15.100 --> 00:00:16.220
Scripps Research Institute,

6
00:00:17.300 --> 00:00:21.220
and I'm incredibly excited to host this

7
00:00:21.260 --> 00:00:23.820
very special session. As many of you know,

8
00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:27.890
the Chemistry to the Clinic sessions are put on each year by the Chemistry and

9
00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:28.640
Cancer Research

10
00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:30.120
working group,

11
00:00:30.980 --> 00:00:34.820
giving us a dedicated platform for chemists and biologists, physicians, data

12
00:00:34.860 --> 00:00:38.540
scientists across academia and industry to come together

13
00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:42.430
with the focus of therapeutic innovation, talking about

14
00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:45.200
the chemistry of new medicines.

15
00:00:46.900 --> 00:00:50.300
Proximity pharmacology unlocks two quite monumental

16
00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:54.120
advances in chemical biology and therapeutic science, the ability to address

17
00:00:54.200 --> 00:00:58.180
targets that are conventionally unligandable and the ability

18
00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:02.080
to rewire the endogenous machinery of cancer cells to act

19
00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:05.960
on some therapeutic target or pathway or process, turning the cell

20
00:01:06.020 --> 00:01:09.860
against itself. We'll hear much more about this

21
00:01:10.860 --> 00:01:14.390
from our speakers today, William Gibson from the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and

22
00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:16.880
Steven Banic from Stanford University.

23
00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:22.130
And I will get us started with a new story emerging from

24
00:01:22.160 --> 00:01:26.060
my laboratory in which we discovered a novel class of

25
00:01:26.100 --> 00:01:29.360
heterobifunctional small molecules that can

26
00:01:29.900 --> 00:01:32.780
rewire DNA repair processes.

27
00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:38.440
One moment, please.

28
00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:46.100
None of this seems to be working.

29
00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:53.060
Okay, he's coming up to help you.

30
00:01:57.980 --> 00:01:59.220
Do I need to use the laptop?

31
00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:03.820
Oh, thanks.

32
00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:07.520
Now nothing seems to advance here.

33
00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:16.220
Okay, we'll use this.

34
00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:20.460
Fantastic. Thank you everyone for your patience. Sorry about that.

35
00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:25.390
So my laboratory is principally interested in understanding

36
00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:28.880
gene regulatory control, or at least this is what we got focused on when we started

37
00:02:28.920 --> 00:02:32.470
the lab. We want to use small molecule tools as biological

38
00:02:32.560 --> 00:02:34.160
reagents to understand the

39
00:02:35.280 --> 00:02:39.200
mechanistic underpinnings of transcriptional control in tumor agenesis and

40
00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:43.200
identify targets and pathways that we can intercept with small molecules.

41
00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:46.960
But more and more recently, we have

42
00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:51.780
picked up quite a focus on induced proximity, proximity

43
00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:55.520
pharmacology as a way to access new targets in transcriptional regulatory control

44
00:02:55.540 --> 00:02:59.220
that we haven't previously been able to address.

45
00:02:59.700 --> 00:03:03.620
And we've embarked on some new territory that I'll share

46
00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:04.280
with you today.

47
00:03:05.340 --> 00:03:08.960
These are small molecules that bind simultaneously to PARP

48
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.740
enzymes and the BET family of transcriptional co-regulators and have

49
00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:16.580
some quite unanticipated effects in the processes of

50
00:03:16.620 --> 00:03:19.600
DNA damage repair, and I'll go into some of that today.

51
00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:23.360
There are many more questions, I think it's fair to say, than answers, but

52
00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:27.760
this is quite an exciting new area of research for us, and I think

53
00:03:27.820 --> 00:03:31.780
that it might be of interest to many that are in this field.

54
00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:37.080
If you'll indulge me just for one quick moment, I'll explain how we got in this

55
00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:40.280
area of DNA damage repair from transcriptional regulatory

56
00:03:40.320 --> 00:03:44.100
control. And it really stems from our collaborative

57
00:03:44.140 --> 00:03:47.480
work with Ben Cravatt's group. Through his

58
00:03:47.520 --> 00:03:51.180
pioneering platforms in activity-based protein profiling, we were

59
00:03:51.220 --> 00:03:54.690
lucky to collaborate with them on a discovery of a small molecule that

60
00:03:54.720 --> 00:03:58.160
binds to a cysteine within the DNA

61
00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:02.310
binding domain of the pioneer and proto-oncogenic transcription factor,

62
00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:03.030
FOXA1.

63
00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:08.100
This small molecule had quite unanticipated activity in living

64
00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:11.609
cells, in prostate cancer cells, that changes the motifs that are recognized by

65
00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:15.280
FOXA1, creating thousands of new binding sites for this

66
00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:17.380
oncogenic transcription factor on the genome.

67
00:04:17.860 --> 00:04:21.421
And it does that by stabilizing small

68
00:04:22.680 --> 00:04:25.740
interactions between FOXA1 and what are

69
00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:29.840
weak DNA binding motifs. The

70
00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:32.810
sequences that it alters the specificity for

71
00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:38.530
are in direct proximity to where this cysteine is located in three-dimensional

72
00:04:38.620 --> 00:04:42.360
space, and we think that there might be some interaction

73
00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:45.840
between the small molecule and the nucleic acids in that region

74
00:04:46.940 --> 00:04:47.700
altering the

75
00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:54.100
binary complex of FOXA1 on DNA. One

76
00:04:54.140 --> 00:04:58.040
thought, and we don't have a structure yet to know exactly how the molecular

77
00:04:58.050 --> 00:05:01.570
recognition occurs here, but one thought is that the small molecule might actually

78
00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:05.440
insert into DNA at a composite pocket and

79
00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:09.480
interface formed between that loop where cysteine 258 resides and the minor

80
00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:10.360
groove of DNA,

81
00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:14.620
and maybe that's responsible for the changes in sequence

82
00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:16.800
specificity that occur in that region.

83
00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:19.600
And there's some precedent for this in the literature.

84
00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:23.820
There are these beautiful molecules from GSK that insert

85
00:05:23.880 --> 00:05:27.780
into DNA and inhibit DNA methyltransferases by

86
00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:31.560
binding exclusively to this composite pocket formed between protein and nucleic

87
00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:35.140
acids. And we've known for many years now gyrase inhibitors

88
00:05:35.600 --> 00:05:39.520
that do a similar thing in a more bifunctional way, inserting

89
00:05:39.600 --> 00:05:43.200
into DNA, intercalating into DNA, but simultaneously

90
00:05:43.240 --> 00:05:47.220
engaging topoisomerase. And the interesting fact of these small

91
00:05:47.280 --> 00:05:50.250
molecules is that although they intercalate in the context of the protein that's

92
00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:52.800
present, they can't intercalate into DNA on their own.

93
00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:56.740
So there's this context dependent ability to bind DNA that's probably

94
00:05:56.800 --> 00:05:59.560
seeded by some very weak affinity for

95
00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:03.620
DNAAnd so we've been wondering if this is maybe a generalizable approach

96
00:06:03.700 --> 00:06:05.120
for going after transcription factors.

97
00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:08.940
Maybe the learnings from FOXA1 could be generalized to other classes of

98
00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:12.480
high-value therapeutic targets in the transcription factor space.

99
00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:18.060
But first, we wanted to understand the principles of what you could do with small

100
00:06:18.100 --> 00:06:20.100
molecules that trap proteins onto DNA.

101
00:06:20.140 --> 00:06:23.280
And so we've been exploring this in a more modular and

102
00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:26.360
heterobifunctional way as we try to

103
00:06:26.960 --> 00:06:29.220
continue our exploration of this space.

104
00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:33.760
To do this, we designed heterobifunctional small molecules that

105
00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:37.970
leverage the trapping capacity of conventional PARP inhibitors.

106
00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:42.000
PARP is a DNA repair enzyme that recognizes single-stranded DNA breaks,

107
00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:46.660
and PARP inhibitors are very well known to elicit synthetic lethality

108
00:06:46.700 --> 00:06:50.370
with homologous recombination deficiencies by virtue of this

109
00:06:50.420 --> 00:06:53.180
trapping activity of PARP inhibitors.

110
00:06:53.240 --> 00:06:56.569
So when PARP is inhibited on DNA, it becomes

111
00:06:56.600 --> 00:07:00.220
immobilized onto those sites of DNA damage, and that

112
00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:04.180
creates a toxic species to the cell that is more detrimental

113
00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:07.460
to cell viability than is PARP loss of

114
00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.000
function. In fact,

115
00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:13.790
we know from genetic studies that if you knock out PARP1,

116
00:07:14.980 --> 00:07:18.470
tumors become quite resistant to the effects of PARP inhibition,

117
00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.480
highlighting this gain-of-function toxicity of PARP inhibition, and that

118
00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:25.320
stems from this trapping capacity.

119
00:07:26.660 --> 00:07:30.240
So we wondered if this would give us a very nice modular

120
00:07:30.320 --> 00:07:34.200
handle in which we could design then heterobifunctional molecules

121
00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:38.180
that use PARP trapping as an

122
00:07:38.260 --> 00:07:42.240
anchor to bring other proteins ectopically to sites of DNA

123
00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:45.300
damage, and what might we learn from that experience.

124
00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:47.040
This is work led by

125
00:07:48.020 --> 00:07:50.760
three really talented members in the group, a post-doc, Bryce de Camara,

126
00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:55.310
Eric Belota, who will be defending his thesis soon, and Aaron Broderick, who's

127
00:07:56.180 --> 00:07:57.500
just a couple years more junior.

128
00:08:00.260 --> 00:08:04.120
In getting started on this idea, we decided to utilize

129
00:08:04.140 --> 00:08:07.820
BET bromodomain inhibitors for the exogenous recruitment of other proteins to

130
00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:10.909
DNA damage, and that was a somewhat marriage of convenience.

131
00:08:10.980 --> 00:08:14.790
The chemistry is quite easy there, but also PARP and BET bromodomain proteins

132
00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:18.400
are in many of the same places at the same time, involved in transcriptional

133
00:08:18.480 --> 00:08:22.430
regulation and also DNA repair. And we thought they might have a great number of

134
00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:25.490
opportunities to interfere with each other's function or create some sort of

135
00:08:25.500 --> 00:08:27.900
gain-of-function effect in the cell.

136
00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:31.900
And to understand that these molecules were doing anything, we first asked

137
00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:35.841
the question of whether they are engaging their targets and whether we

138
00:08:35.900 --> 00:08:39.610
see effects in the cells. This is a BRD4 target

139
00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:43.380
engagement assay, where you can see JQ1, the prototypical BET

140
00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:46.640
bromodomain inhibitor, having very nice engagement of BRD4.

141
00:08:47.040 --> 00:08:50.600
And our PSIP molecules showed a little bit of BET bromodomain engagement, but it

142
00:08:50.620 --> 00:08:54.520
was quite severely reduced. And I'll bring your attention to this compound

143
00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:55.400
2, PSIP1,

144
00:08:56.620 --> 00:09:00.060
where we saw severely diminished BET bromodomain

145
00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:00.880
engagement.

146
00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:03.740
And the story was similar for PARP.

147
00:09:04.260 --> 00:09:08.040
So we see almost undetectable PARP1 engagement in these cells with

148
00:09:08.320 --> 00:09:11.780
the small molecule PSIP1. And despite those weak

149
00:09:12.240 --> 00:09:13.980
binary engagement

150
00:09:15.420 --> 00:09:16.040
profiles,

151
00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:19.200
PSIP1 had this

152
00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:24.140
cytotoxicity that was equivalent to BET bromodomain inhibition,

153
00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:27.860
more severe than PARP inhibition.

154
00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:32.200
And so this brought up one of two possibilities in our mind.

155
00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:36.120
Perhaps we had picked up some unfortunate off-target effect,

156
00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:40.100
just inhibiting polo kinase or something unanticipated, or they might be

157
00:09:40.160 --> 00:09:42.680
functioning through proximity pharmacology.

158
00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:47.160
Even though we have very weak equilibrium engagement of

159
00:09:47.260 --> 00:09:51.200
both ends of the target, that doesn't exclude the possibility that we're creating

160
00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:54.900
a low stoichiometry ternary complex that has some

161
00:09:54.940 --> 00:09:57.700
durable biological effect through

162
00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:00.780
some kind of irreversible event.

163
00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:05.680
And I hope I'll convince you that it's the second option.

164
00:10:06.500 --> 00:10:09.780
This is an assay where we looked at whether these molecules

165
00:10:09.790 --> 00:10:13.640
preserved synthetic lethality with HR deficiencies, a DLD1 BRCA2

166
00:10:13.880 --> 00:10:17.829
isogenic knockout model. And we can see that like rucaparib, PSIP1

167
00:10:17.900 --> 00:10:21.199
has a major shift in potency in the absence of

168
00:10:21.220 --> 00:10:24.300
BRCA2. This is not experienced by BET bromodomain

169
00:10:24.340 --> 00:10:28.040
inhibition. But we see this nice preserved

170
00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:29.180
synthetic lethality.

171
00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:34.280
And that toxicity is totally removed by

172
00:10:34.340 --> 00:10:37.780
inverting the stereochemistry on the JQ1 portion of these small

173
00:10:37.840 --> 00:10:40.760
molecules. The stereoisomer can't engage BET

174
00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:44.640
bromodomains. And we see no cell viability effects with the

175
00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:48.630
small molecule, suggesting that although we're not stoichiometrically engaging

176
00:10:48.640 --> 00:10:52.620
BET bromodomains, it is required for the mechanism of action, suggesting that

177
00:10:52.660 --> 00:10:55.740
maybe there was some sort of heterobifunctional activity

178
00:10:56.240 --> 00:10:58.680
elicited by these cells or by these compounds.

179
00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:03.780
But to confirm that we actually do create a ternary complex, we designed

180
00:11:03.860 --> 00:11:07.300
a FRET-based assay to look at proximity between PARP and

181
00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:10.120
BRD4. And here we see a very

182
00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:14.880
typical hook effect suggestive of induced proximity

183
00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:18.660
that is ablated by the inverted

184
00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:21.260
stereoisomer, the enantiomer of PSIP1.

185
00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:25.450
And so we can confirm that at least in vitro, these small molecules do

186
00:11:27.220 --> 00:11:28.740
elicit a ternary complex.

187
00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:33.280
And the same holds true in cells. So if you do a BRD4

188
00:11:33.400 --> 00:11:36.420
pull-down and look for co-elution of

189
00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:40.670
PARP1 and PARP2, we see that only in the presence of PSIP1, not in either of

190
00:11:40.700 --> 00:11:44.020
the monovalent controls or the inactive enantiomer.

191
00:11:44.040 --> 00:11:47.850
And if you do the reverse pull-down PARP2, we see BRD4 come along

192
00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:48.280
with it.

193
00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:51.160
So in vitro and in cells, we can

194
00:11:52.960 --> 00:11:55.380
see evidence of ternary complex formation by PSIP1.

195
00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.920
And this, as we expected based on the synthetic lethality with HR

196
00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:03.680
deficiencies, leads to a very potent inhibition of DNA damage

197
00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:06.160
repair. So in the presence of an exogenous

198
00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:10.428
source of DNA damage with this MMS-...

199
00:12:10.438 --> 00:12:13.908
chemical mutagen, we see that rucaparib inhibits

200
00:12:13.928 --> 00:12:17.568
polyolation by PARP1 and creates a high

201
00:12:17.588 --> 00:12:21.288
burden of DNA damage as read out by gamma-H2AX.

202
00:12:21.828 --> 00:12:23.828
And the same thing is seen with PSIP1,

203
00:12:25.528 --> 00:12:29.348
confirming that these molecules are most likely working through some sort of

204
00:12:29.488 --> 00:12:32.108
DNA damage response, and that correlates with

205
00:12:33.188 --> 00:12:37.068
a cell cycle arrest in the S phase, which is quite similar

206
00:12:37.108 --> 00:12:38.048
to PARP inhibition.

207
00:12:39.968 --> 00:12:43.768
And if you perform a prism assay with the Broad Institute, we see an incredibly

208
00:12:43.988 --> 00:12:47.648
high correlation between PSIP1 and selective PARP1

209
00:12:47.688 --> 00:12:48.968
inhibitors like sinaprib,

210
00:12:50.008 --> 00:12:53.448
the top correlated compounds of over 25,000 comparisons.

211
00:12:54.238 --> 00:12:58.168
And this follows a dose-response relationship where at low concentrations of

212
00:12:58.188 --> 00:13:00.768
the compound, we see a very high correlation with PARP inhibition.

213
00:13:01.348 --> 00:13:04.268
At very high concentrations, we start to see things correlate with BET bromodomain

214
00:13:04.308 --> 00:13:07.938
inhibition, but I think that's a nice confirmation that the molecule's not

215
00:13:07.968 --> 00:13:10.808
functioning as a BET bromodomain inhibitor, at least when we're careful about the

216
00:13:10.848 --> 00:13:13.588
concentrations that we use them at, which we are.

217
00:13:15.848 --> 00:13:18.227
And this was an unexpected result to us.

218
00:13:18.268 --> 00:13:22.028
We did not anticipate that BET recruitment would be cytotoxic or that it would

219
00:13:22.068 --> 00:13:25.688
inhibit DNA damage repair. And so we've had a number of questions about how

220
00:13:25.728 --> 00:13:29.168
this effect could be caused in the cells.

221
00:13:30.888 --> 00:13:34.518
One thought was that maybe this leads to PARP1 trapping,

222
00:13:34.708 --> 00:13:38.388
like conventional PARP inhibitors, and that that's the source of the

223
00:13:38.408 --> 00:13:41.568
cytotoxicity. But we very quickly ruled that out.

224
00:13:41.628 --> 00:13:45.478
In fact, if you knock out PARP1, the cells become more sensitive to PSIP1,

225
00:13:45.608 --> 00:13:49.528
quite opposite of the control compound here, talazoparib, where you see a rapid

226
00:13:49.588 --> 00:13:53.388
emergence of resistance. We actually see an improved sensitivity of these

227
00:13:53.428 --> 00:13:54.468
cells to PSIP1.

228
00:13:55.728 --> 00:13:57.688
So we thought, "Well, maybe it's PARP2 then.

229
00:13:57.728 --> 00:14:01.628
I don't know why, but it could be." And we knocked out PARP2, and indeed, that gave

230
00:14:01.688 --> 00:14:05.448
very rapid resistance to PSIP1, not something that we see with other PARP

231
00:14:05.468 --> 00:14:06.048
inhibitors.

232
00:14:07.248 --> 00:14:08.848
And so then we

233
00:14:10.428 --> 00:14:13.768
became quite convinced that the ternary complex formed

234
00:14:14.628 --> 00:14:18.357
between BET bromodomain proteins and PARP2 is the source of toxicity,

235
00:14:18.788 --> 00:14:22.708
and PARP1, which is quite a bit more abundant in the cells,

236
00:14:23.188 --> 00:14:26.008
might act as a sink for the compound, a non-functional sink.

237
00:14:26.048 --> 00:14:29.028
When we form a ternary complex with PARP1, it doesn't do anything.

238
00:14:29.048 --> 00:14:32.288
And so in the absence of this very abundant protein, we get improved

239
00:14:32.328 --> 00:14:33.218
cytotoxicity.

240
00:14:34.188 --> 00:14:38.068
Indeed, when you knock out PARP2, PSIP1 is no longer able to inhibit the

241
00:14:38.128 --> 00:14:41.788
repair of DNA damage. We see the loss of gamma-H2AX in

242
00:14:42.128 --> 00:14:45.868
the absence of PARP2. And we have this very nice chemical control where we

243
00:14:45.928 --> 00:14:49.768
can titrate increasing concentrations of several PARP inhibitors that

244
00:14:49.848 --> 00:14:53.608
all have equivalent PARP1 potency but vary in their

245
00:14:53.648 --> 00:14:57.488
PARP2 affinities by over three orders of magnitude and ask

246
00:14:57.568 --> 00:14:57.788
at

