00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:00.860
and then brought them to the clinic.

740
00:43:00.920 --> 00:43:02.310
And you can see here they did their

741
00:43:04.800 --> 00:43:06.190
initial dose-finding studies.

742
00:43:07.010 --> 00:43:10.780
And what was found is that very quickly, within a week, these patients dropped

743
00:43:10.800 --> 00:43:12.480
their platelet counts precipitously.

744
00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:15.250
So it turns out these patients were

745
00:43:16.960 --> 00:43:20.859
initially tried in melanoma, which has very high expression of PD3A and Slufn 12,

746
00:43:22.340 --> 00:43:22.640
that

747
00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:25.380
the compounds were killing megakaryocytes.

748
00:43:26.220 --> 00:43:29.130
And then you'd see the platelet drop about a week later because platelets have a

749
00:43:29.160 --> 00:43:30.270
half-life of about a week.

750
00:43:31.580 --> 00:43:34.740
And if you go back to the very first panels from the original

751
00:43:35.500 --> 00:43:38.980
Velcan papers, you can see there's some PD3A inhibitors that are

752
00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:42.519
non-toxic, some that are. And amongst those that are, is a compound called

753
00:43:42.540 --> 00:43:44.840
anagrelide. Anagrelide has been

754
00:43:45.760 --> 00:43:49.720
FDA approved as a treatment for thrombocythemia

755
00:43:50.280 --> 00:43:53.820
to reduce platelets when they're pathologically high.

756
00:43:54.180 --> 00:43:57.790
So something I think we keep seeing in the induced proximity field is that

757
00:43:58.540 --> 00:44:00.710
what's old is new, what's new is old,

758
00:44:01.780 --> 00:44:05.160
with thalidomide, lenalidomide, and now Velcans, is that you keep

759
00:44:05.220 --> 00:44:08.920
rediscovering these really interesting PPIs and these small molecules that

760
00:44:08.960 --> 00:44:09.560
induce them.

761
00:44:11.280 --> 00:44:11.460
So

762
00:44:12.300 --> 00:44:15.120
it turned out that this was hiding under our nose all this time.

763
00:44:17.540 --> 00:44:19.740
Now switching topics to another set of induced

764
00:44:19.760 --> 00:44:21.750
proximity

765
00:44:23.400 --> 00:44:26.700
phenotypes that we think is really interesting is this discovery of this Riptak

766
00:44:26.720 --> 00:44:29.700
principle. So Craig Crews and how the therapeutics showed that

767
00:44:30.600 --> 00:44:34.360
if you take cancers overexpressing a certain protein and design small

768
00:44:34.420 --> 00:44:37.760
molecules that are targeting this protein, and then also bearing

769
00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:41.960
a molecule that targets some essential protein, you

770
00:44:41.980 --> 00:44:45.140
can see dramatically enhanced toxicity in the cells that are

771
00:44:45.220 --> 00:44:48.320
overexpressing what they call the target protein, here depicted in

772
00:44:48.360 --> 00:44:49.540
purple.

773
00:44:50.360 --> 00:44:54.140
So all you need is this, for selectivity, is to find a protein that's highly

774
00:44:54.200 --> 00:44:55.580
overabundant in the cancer cells.

775
00:44:56.680 --> 00:45:00.620
So here in their cell chemical biology paper in 2024, they

776
00:45:00.680 --> 00:45:04.140
show if you take a parental cell line, overexpress

777
00:45:04.440 --> 00:45:08.260
FKBP, and then use these bifunctional ligands, you can get a really

778
00:45:10.060 --> 00:45:14.020
interesting therapeutic index. And here the essential protein

779
00:45:14.080 --> 00:45:15.240
is a CDK inhibitor.

780
00:45:16.940 --> 00:45:20.720
Now they have progressed this to the clinic in, I think, a really impressive way.

781
00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:23.520
So their first set of products was

782
00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:27.380
bifunctional compounds that were targeting the androgen receptor,

783
00:45:28.340 --> 00:45:31.000
and bringing BRD4 as the essential protein to it.

784
00:45:31.600 --> 00:45:35.320
So this is Halda 0915. So January,

785
00:45:35.900 --> 00:45:39.360
2023 was the Riptak preprint. And very quickly, they

786
00:45:40.580 --> 00:45:43.080
got to clinic in 2025 with their trial launch.

787
00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:46.300
October 25, they got these trial results, which we'll go over.

788
00:45:46.360 --> 00:45:48.200
So this is their dose-finding study.

789
00:45:48.240 --> 00:45:51.770
At 50 milligrams daily dose, you can see they reached

790
00:45:52.260 --> 00:45:56.250
very high efficacy. And what was really impressive to me was not just this

791
00:45:56.300 --> 00:45:59.840
waterfall plot, but these were patients that were already castrate resistant.

792
00:46:00.330 --> 00:46:03.920
Androgen receptor had been inhibited every which way before these patients were

793
00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:07.770
enrolled. So presumably, these tumors were

794
00:46:07.960 --> 00:46:08.780
resistant to

795
00:46:09.740 --> 00:46:13.660
a loss of androgen signaling. And when you look at these patients, you actually

796
00:46:13.720 --> 00:46:17.590
see that lots of them have AR ligand binding mutations, even the ones that

797
00:46:17.640 --> 00:46:21.609
responded. And lots of them are expressing ARV7, lacking this

798
00:46:21.660 --> 00:46:23.840
ligand binding domain entirely. So

799
00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:28.280
presumably,

800
00:46:28.300 --> 00:46:30.640
this cannot be due to a loss of AR signaling.

801
00:46:31.580 --> 00:46:35.460
It has to be due to the presence of the wild-type proteins in these

802
00:46:35.500 --> 00:46:39.309
cells, and then this gain of function pharmacology where you're

803
00:46:39.320 --> 00:46:43.110
bringing BRD4 to them. So just

804
00:46:43.440 --> 00:46:46.660
one month after they presented these results, they were acquired for three billion

805
00:46:46.680 --> 00:46:47.320
by J&amp;J.

806
00:46:48.620 --> 00:46:52.160
And so one thought we've had is, can we apply these learnings to other cancer

807
00:46:52.180 --> 00:46:52.760
proteins?

808
00:46:54.860 --> 00:46:58.440
And one protein where we've been excited about applying these concepts is with

809
00:46:58.480 --> 00:46:59.230
P53.

810
00:47:00.100 --> 00:47:03.870
So P53 is the most mutated protein across all

811
00:47:03.900 --> 00:47:05.920
cancers, and it's not really close.

812
00:47:06.860 --> 00:47:08.860
And it's the worst mutation to have, too.

813
00:47:09.140 --> 00:47:13.020
So on the right-hand side of this plot, you can see a bunch of genetic subtypes of

814
00:47:13.060 --> 00:47:16.590
acute myeloid leukemia, and the patients who actually die of their disease are the

815
00:47:16.600 --> 00:47:20.440
patients with P53 mutations. So when you add all this up, that's about five

816
00:47:20.540 --> 00:47:23.680
million patients per year that die of P53 mutant disease.

817
00:47:25.300 --> 00:47:29.270
P53 mutations are fairly interesting in a few ways, but one is

818
00:47:29.320 --> 00:47:32.400
that for most tumor suppressors, they're knocked out by

819
00:47:32.840 --> 00:47:36.160
nonsense or frame shift mutations, but P53,

820
00:47:36.520 --> 00:47:39.480
75% of these mutations are missense mutations.

821
00:47:40.090 --> 00:47:41.660
And that's because these mutations,

822
00:47:42.540 --> 00:47:46.280
95% of them occur in the DNA binding domain, and you need the full

823
00:47:46.340 --> 00:47:49.640
tetramer to wrap around DNA at the right sites in the genome.

824
00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:53.330
And if any one of those tetrameric subunits is

825
00:47:53.720 --> 00:47:56.840
mutated, you lose that DNA binding ability at the right places.

826
00:47:56.890 --> 00:48:00.750
So it's a faster path for P53 to take these

827
00:48:00.800 --> 00:48:03.059
missense dominant negative mutations.

828
00:48:04.220 --> 00:48:05.000
So

829
00:48:06.400 --> 00:48:10.330
we've looked in the past for synthetic lethals against P53 and

830
00:48:10.340 --> 00:48:14.180
never found any. So if you ask yourself, what is different about P53 mutant

831
00:48:14.200 --> 00:48:17.120
cells versus wild-type cells, you really only come up with one thing.

832
00:48:17.240 --> 00:48:20.640
So when you do quantitative proteomics across the whole proteome,

833
00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:25.140
you see that only one protein is increased in abundance, and that's P53

834
00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:28.900
itself. And that's because there's this tight feedback loop between

835
00:48:28.980 --> 00:48:32.920
MDM2 and P53, and when you lose P53's ability

836
00:48:33.020 --> 00:48:35.760
to transcribe MDM2, you build up very high levels of

837
00:48:35.780 --> 00:48:39.468
P53.So here is what that looks like

838
00:48:39.528 --> 00:48:42.428
across the Cancer Cell Line Encyclopedia.

839
00:48:42.468 --> 00:48:45.908
All the cell lines that have missense mutations of p53 have very high

840
00:48:46.348 --> 00:48:48.908
abundance of p53 protein on the Y-axis.

841
00:48:50.308 --> 00:48:50.588
And

842
00:48:51.728 --> 00:48:55.468
this is actually how we used to diagnose p53 mutant cancers, which is we would do

843
00:48:55.568 --> 00:48:59.508
IHC for p53. So on the right, you can see an

844
00:48:59.548 --> 00:49:03.488
ovarian cancer sample, H&amp;E on the left, p53 staining on the right.

845
00:49:03.688 --> 00:49:07.368
The normal stroma has essentially zero p53. The cancer cells have a lot of it.

846
00:49:07.418 --> 00:49:09.028
So when I see a

847
00:49:11.108 --> 00:49:14.078
immunohistochemistry like that, I think, "Well, that's a therapeutic window I can

848
00:49:14.088 --> 00:49:17.888
work with." So the idea is that we need a

849
00:49:17.898 --> 00:49:21.688
drug that kills cells in proportion of p53 abundance, and the molecular glue and

850
00:49:21.708 --> 00:49:23.238
RIP-TAG framework fits that bill.

851
00:49:24.308 --> 00:49:27.857
So we designed small molecules looking through the patent literature that could

852
00:49:27.868 --> 00:49:31.618
bind to p53. And we know that there's no molecules that can

853
00:49:31.648 --> 00:49:35.588
bind to wild type p53 or pockets that are

854
00:49:35.628 --> 00:49:37.428
native to a large variety of mutants.

855
00:49:37.508 --> 00:49:40.328
But there are molecules that can bind to the Y220C mutant.

856
00:49:41.028 --> 00:49:42.508
So we designed a molecule that

857
00:49:43.468 --> 00:49:47.428
binds to this Y220C mutant and recruits PLK1, which is

858
00:49:47.488 --> 00:49:49.288
a highly essential mitotic kinase.

859
00:49:50.208 --> 00:49:54.168
We were able to show that you can get specific cell death in these cells that bear

860
00:49:54.188 --> 00:49:57.158
the Y220C mutation and not those that bear other

861
00:49:57.568 --> 00:50:01.228
p53 mutations, and that you don't see any effect from either of the

862
00:50:01.268 --> 00:50:05.088
monomeric binders, PLK1 inhibitors or the

863
00:50:05.128 --> 00:50:06.708
p53 binder itself.

864
00:50:07.868 --> 00:50:11.388
We can see that you can easily reconstitute a ternary complex

865
00:50:11.428 --> 00:50:13.028
formation in NanoBiT assays,

866
00:50:14.028 --> 00:50:17.888
and that when you add excess of the monomeric binder you

867
00:50:17.928 --> 00:50:21.908
can rescue some of the toxicity. So we do think that this is a gain of function

868
00:50:22.788 --> 00:50:26.248
pharmacology that's dependent on the ternary complex.

869
00:50:27.108 --> 00:50:30.908
When we add our compound to cells, we observed that of course the

870
00:50:30.948 --> 00:50:33.008
p53 refolder can induce

871
00:50:34.088 --> 00:50:36.028
p53 transcriptional activation.

872
00:50:36.708 --> 00:50:40.158
But when we add the bivalent compound, we don't see that it's working through

873
00:50:40.188 --> 00:50:41.188
p53

874
00:50:42.788 --> 00:50:43.898
recovery of its function.

875
00:50:44.728 --> 00:50:48.127
And instead, we think that-- So here you can see a heat map of

876
00:50:48.137 --> 00:50:52.068
p53 targets, the PMV6 compound which is from

877
00:50:52.128 --> 00:50:55.988
PMV Pharma, now in risatapapt in clinical trials, can reactivate

878
00:50:56.028 --> 00:50:59.988
these target genes. But the bivalent molecule that brings PLK1

879
00:51:00.028 --> 00:51:03.448
to p53 does not, and is likely acting much

880
00:51:04.048 --> 00:51:07.447
more through PLK1 inhibition in a RIP-TAG-like manner.

881
00:51:08.788 --> 00:51:12.748
So now I'll transition to a new story that we just put

882
00:51:12.788 --> 00:51:14.228
out in a preprint, which is

883
00:51:15.668 --> 00:51:19.628
that some of these molecules you think you can intend to work

884
00:51:19.648 --> 00:51:22.308
one way, and it actually turns out they have a few different functions.

885
00:51:22.388 --> 00:51:23.088
So

886
00:51:24.308 --> 00:51:28.298
the same bifunctional compound can be a TSIP, a RIP-TAG, a degrader, and a

887
00:51:28.328 --> 00:51:30.088
whole bunch of other things. So I'll go through how we

888
00:51:30.928 --> 00:51:31.577
learned about this.

889
00:51:32.508 --> 00:51:36.438
So we were trying to find small molecules or do a comprehensive assessment

890
00:51:36.468 --> 00:51:40.348
of what are the best warheads you could use to recruit transcription.

891
00:51:40.428 --> 00:51:43.828
So we had used an IRF1 reporter. We used

892
00:51:44.928 --> 00:51:48.448
FKBP tagged IRF1 to drag transcriptional

893
00:51:48.488 --> 00:51:50.908
machinery through a variety of different warheads to

894
00:51:52.028 --> 00:51:55.868
IRF1. And what we found was the most potent warhead

895
00:51:56.068 --> 00:51:59.628
was this p300 recruiting warhead called GNE-781.

896
00:52:00.108 --> 00:52:02.167
It's at the top of this plot here, ATAC2.

897
00:52:03.668 --> 00:52:07.308
So we tried to do a little linkerology with the different linkers

898
00:52:07.328 --> 00:52:09.588
depicted here. And what we saw was that

899
00:52:10.688 --> 00:52:14.248
we get transactivation in the IRF1 reporter and dose response studies.

900
00:52:15.208 --> 00:52:18.328
You can compete off this transactivation with excess binder.

901
00:52:18.357 --> 00:52:20.548
It's characteristic of these ternary complexes.

902
00:52:21.828 --> 00:52:23.668
And that you can bring

903
00:52:25.128 --> 00:52:25.908
CBP

904
00:52:26.708 --> 00:52:28.488
in ternary complex and NanoBiT assays.

905
00:52:30.108 --> 00:52:34.088
And so what we thought is, okay, so we have a small molecule that can activate

906
00:52:34.488 --> 00:52:38.288
transcriptional machinery. And we thought, well, what are some models where we

907
00:52:38.308 --> 00:52:41.628
could try this therapeutically? And one model that's been used in the past that I

908
00:52:41.668 --> 00:52:45.448
think I thought was really compelling is a model of therapeutic overactivation.

909
00:52:45.528 --> 00:52:48.648
So it's been known since about 2002 that if you overexpress

910
00:52:48.808 --> 00:52:52.788
EWS-FLI, the Ewing sarcoma oncogene in fibroblasts, that

911
00:52:52.848 --> 00:52:54.808
they'll die off if you express at high levels.

912
00:52:55.768 --> 00:52:59.648
And if you knock out the ubiquitin ligase for EWS-FLI,

913
00:52:59.808 --> 00:53:02.948
TRIM8, then the cells will also die.

914
00:53:03.088 --> 00:53:06.468
So we thought maybe we can add our compound, overactivate

915
00:53:06.508 --> 00:53:08.928
EWS-FLI, and have a therapeutic response.

916
00:53:09.568 --> 00:53:13.048
And it turned out when we did RNA sequencing with this

917
00:53:13.088 --> 00:53:16.908
GNE-871 compound that we saw a decrease in the

918
00:53:16.948 --> 00:53:18.268
EWS-FLI program.

919
00:53:19.128 --> 00:53:23.088
And I asked my student a few times, "Did you mix up the tubes?" We went

920
00:53:23.148 --> 00:53:25.128
back, tried it again, got the same result.

921
00:53:25.768 --> 00:53:29.208
And it turned out it was really real, that this compound was not actually inducing

922
00:53:29.218 --> 00:53:33.088
transcription. It was actually inducing a loss of the transcriptional program.

923
00:53:33.168 --> 00:53:35.028
So we scratched our heads and tried all the things.

924
00:53:35.588 --> 00:53:38.528
We found out that the compound was degrading EWS-FLI.

925
00:53:39.148 --> 00:53:40.448
You can see in this Western blot here.

926
00:53:41.288 --> 00:53:42.858
But what was also happening is that

927
00:53:43.868 --> 00:53:46.998
EWS-FLI, which typically recruits p300

928
00:53:48.128 --> 00:53:51.768
to EWS-FLI bound sites, was actually exchanging CBP.

929
00:53:51.868 --> 00:53:55.648
So when we did ChIP-seq, we saw recruitment of CBP, loss of

930
00:53:55.688 --> 00:53:56.758
p300 peaks.

931
00:53:58.188 --> 00:54:01.478
And that when we repeated these experiments with just

932
00:54:01.528 --> 00:54:05.498
FKBP GFP knocked into these cells rather than the EWS-FLI with

933
00:54:05.608 --> 00:54:08.708
FKBP, we could find the same toxic effects.

934
00:54:09.248 --> 00:54:09.888
And so what we

935
00:54:11.008 --> 00:54:14.578
thought this molecule was going to act as a TSIP, we actually saw that it was

936
00:54:14.648 --> 00:54:17.488
acting as a RIP-TAG and a degrader of the

937
00:54:18.448 --> 00:54:19.268
fusion oncogene.

938
00:54:20.128 --> 00:54:23.798
And the lesson here is that bifunctional compounds don't just have one mode of

939
00:54:23.868 --> 00:54:27.728
action. They can do a lot of things at once, and you really have to do the work to

940
00:54:27.768 --> 00:54:28.428
piece it all out.

941
00:54:29.848 --> 00:54:33.388
So with that, I just want to wrap up and thank all my lab

942
00:54:33.428 --> 00:54:36.928
members, especially Ananth Than, who did the work on the

943
00:54:37.308 --> 00:54:41.018
ATAC story and the p53 story. And I want to thank our funding,

944
00:54:42.068 --> 00:54:43.488
especially the Briger Foundation.

945
00:54:43.528 --> 00:54:46.548
And please feel free to reach out, and I'll take any questions.

946
00:54:56.280 --> 00:54:58.140
Very nice talk. I just have a question.

947
00:54:58.240 --> 00:55:01.100
So for the RIP-tag, you're using p53.

948
00:55:01.500 --> 00:55:04.880
You're using a binder which specifically binds the mutated

949
00:55:04.900 --> 00:55:05.720
p53.

950
00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:10.540
Considering the high expression of p53

951
00:55:10.580 --> 00:55:13.640
in mutant cells, is that possible to use a

952
00:55:13.680 --> 00:55:17.280
binder and the wild type p53 as still have

953
00:55:17.360 --> 00:55:19.600
a therapeutic window, do you think?

954
00:55:20.060 --> 00:55:23.740
Yeah. So we did some experiments there in proof of concept

955
00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:24.820
systems using

956
00:55:25.660 --> 00:55:29.360
tagged versions of mutant and wild type p53, and we still

957
00:55:29.500 --> 00:55:31.220
see a good therapeutic index there.

958
00:55:31.340 --> 00:55:34.680
So one of the areas of focus for us is trying to extend

959
00:55:34.720 --> 00:55:38.520
this framework to pan-p53 sort of

960
00:55:38.540 --> 00:55:39.900
RIP-tags and molecular glues.

961
00:55:40.680 --> 00:55:41.320
Okay, thank you.

962
00:55:44.960 --> 00:55:47.140
Thank you for the introductory section and

963
00:55:48.240 --> 00:55:50.040
sharing your beautiful data.

964
00:55:51.080 --> 00:55:54.420
I was wondering about your introductory session.

965
00:55:54.880 --> 00:55:58.540
From the localization case, you showed us

966
00:55:58.660 --> 00:56:02.440
that FKBP is recruited to BRD4's

967
00:56:02.520 --> 00:56:06.360
location, and next case, neo functions

968
00:56:06.420 --> 00:56:10.340
for TCIP. BRD4 is recruited to

969
00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:13.720
BCL6 location. Why does this

970
00:56:13.880 --> 00:56:16.120
difference between these two cases?

971
00:56:16.200 --> 00:56:18.540
Could you share your insight to this difference?

972
00:56:18.580 --> 00:56:19.320
Oh.

973
00:56:19.440 --> 00:56:21.160
So the same BRD4-

974
00:56:21.740 --> 00:56:22.120
Yeah

975
00:56:22.140 --> 00:56:25.820
... when partnering with two proteins,

976
00:56:26.660 --> 00:56:26.940
BRD4

977
00:56:27.900 --> 00:56:28.240
looks.

978
00:56:28.380 --> 00:56:31.080
Yeah. It's a good question. I think there's a few things.

979
00:56:31.520 --> 00:56:35.320
I think a lot of this has to do with the molarity of the two proteins in all of

