00:56:35.360 --> 00:56:39.250
these systems, is that typically the one with higher molarity is going

981
00:56:39.260 --> 00:56:39.980
to win or-

982
00:56:40.390 --> 00:56:40.390
Molarity

983
00:56:40.390 --> 00:56:41.360
... localization.

984
00:56:41.460 --> 00:56:42.860
The abundance.

985
00:56:43.120 --> 00:56:43.240
Yeah.

986
00:56:43.700 --> 00:56:44.420
Oh, thank you.

987
00:56:46.740 --> 00:56:49.140
Hello. Adam from Aurum Therapeutics.

988
00:56:49.940 --> 00:56:53.700
For the p53 degrader, do you require the cells to have

989
00:56:53.720 --> 00:56:56.680
one copy of the wild type p53 for that to work?

990
00:56:58.100 --> 00:57:01.980
No. So yeah, a lot of p53 mutants are heterozygous,

991
00:57:02.020 --> 00:57:04.180
and you still see the accumulation of the protein.

992
00:57:05.060 --> 00:57:08.900
I think what we saw is that the p53 refolders work very well

993
00:57:08.940 --> 00:57:10.360
in the context of

994
00:57:11.340 --> 00:57:14.720
where they're heterozygous where you have a wild type ligand.

995
00:57:14.740 --> 00:57:18.640
But if you have two mutants, like a second hotspot with the

996
00:57:18.700 --> 00:57:22.320
Y220C mutation, the refolders don't work at all, which makes sense.

997
00:57:22.720 --> 00:57:26.060
But we see the gain of function compounds work there as well.

998
00:57:26.900 --> 00:57:29.000
I think I'm still missing a piece of the logic.

999
00:57:29.260 --> 00:57:29.380
You're

1000
00:57:30.400 --> 00:57:32.080
degrading a tumor suppressor?

1001
00:57:32.320 --> 00:57:34.080
I'm sorry. It's not a degrader. It's a

1002
00:57:35.480 --> 00:57:35.959
RIP-tag.

1003
00:57:36.260 --> 00:57:37.020
Ah.

1004
00:57:37.360 --> 00:57:41.240
You can bring in additional toxicity by binding

1005
00:57:41.280 --> 00:57:42.240
to p53.

1006
00:57:42.800 --> 00:57:43.600
Ah. Thank you.

1007
00:57:51.200 --> 00:57:52.600
All right. Thank you, guys.

1008
00:57:58.600 --> 00:58:00.640
Thank you, Will. Next, we'll have

1009
00:58:01.520 --> 00:58:04.960
Steven Banik come and talk more about proximity pharmacology.

1010
00:58:07.800 --> 00:58:09.220
All right. Thank you very much.

1011
00:58:10.680 --> 00:58:13.670
So Will did a really great job talking about

1012
00:58:13.680 --> 00:58:17.080
the evolution of bifunctional molecules.

1013
00:58:18.140 --> 00:58:21.920
And so I figured I would do something a little bit different and think about how

1014
00:58:21.960 --> 00:58:24.960
we discover molecules for induced proximity in the first place.

1015
00:58:26.560 --> 00:58:26.780
So,

1016
00:58:28.400 --> 00:58:32.260
I would say that bifunctional molecules have really been the heart of

1017
00:58:32.280 --> 00:58:34.090
induced proximity therapeutic development.

1018
00:58:34.240 --> 00:58:38.049
So as we saw, they allow us to go all the way

1019
00:58:38.080 --> 00:58:41.840
from protein degradation strategies, where you can think about recruiting

1020
00:58:42.360 --> 00:58:46.280
ubiquitin ligase machinery or directly bringing proteins to a

1021
00:58:46.340 --> 00:58:48.000
subcellular compartment for destruction,

1022
00:58:49.520 --> 00:58:53.370
to then thinking about how we can maybe induce broader post-translational

1023
00:58:53.400 --> 00:58:54.560
modification rewiring

1024
00:58:55.440 --> 00:58:59.160
to enforce signaling or create neo functions or attenuate

1025
00:58:59.180 --> 00:59:01.350
signaling. And then

1026
00:59:01.940 --> 00:59:05.920
this continuum allows us to get to a

1027
00:59:05.960 --> 00:59:09.269
space where we can maybe remove considerations entirely

1028
00:59:09.360 --> 00:59:13.179
about a bespoke function. Does it need to add or remove a

1029
00:59:13.220 --> 00:59:14.830
covalent group to actually do something?

1030
00:59:14.880 --> 00:59:18.500
And so I think we're now seeing that even just bringing two proteins together in

1031
00:59:18.560 --> 00:59:22.460
unique ways allows for a large number of

1032
00:59:22.740 --> 00:59:23.640
rewiring events.

1033
00:59:24.700 --> 00:59:28.150
And so in this space of bringing proteins together, I

1034
00:59:28.160 --> 00:59:32.060
think the reason bifunctionals have been so attractive is because it really allows

1035
00:59:32.100 --> 00:59:34.360
us to program this behavior in some way.

1036
00:59:35.100 --> 00:59:38.960
We can take known ligands or known proteins, couple them together,

1037
00:59:39.320 --> 00:59:41.240
and yes, linkerology is

1038
00:59:42.420 --> 00:59:45.440
maybe arduous, but it is something that we can perform readily.

1039
00:59:45.460 --> 00:59:49.380
We can make lots of compounds by taking known ligands and putting them together.

1040
00:59:49.460 --> 00:59:53.220
And where this has gone to now, I think, is

1041
00:59:53.380 --> 00:59:57.120
trying to find molecules where when you bring them together, induces an extra

1042
00:59:57.180 --> 00:59:59.060
element of cooperativity in that engagement.

1043
00:59:59.180 --> 01:00:03.100
So moving away from this idea that these two proteins

1044
01:00:03.160 --> 01:00:06.980
don't have any inherent interactions to finding molecules that maybe induce them

1045
01:00:07.020 --> 01:00:09.860
to have some sort of affinity interaction as well.

1046
01:00:11.130 --> 01:00:13.580
And these bifunctional molecules come in lots of different flavors for lots of

1047
01:00:13.620 --> 01:00:14.340
different purposes.

1048
01:00:16.680 --> 01:00:20.290
So of course, our ability to do this requires that we have ligands.

1049
01:00:21.080 --> 01:00:24.230
And at some point, we're going to run out of ligands to start putting things

1050
01:00:24.240 --> 01:00:28.060
together and to rewire biology. So how do we discover new molecules?

1051
01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:31.920
And I would say there are a few different

1052
01:00:31.980 --> 01:00:35.560
camps. I would say one major camp is this idea of ligand first.

1053
01:00:36.220 --> 01:00:40.120
You think about trying to find any binder for your protein of

1054
01:00:40.160 --> 01:00:41.640
interest and then repurpose that.

1055
01:00:41.680 --> 01:00:45.520
And so DNA encoded library technology, I think, has really emerged

1056
01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:49.160
as the major way of doing large amounts of bio-panning for any

1057
01:00:49.180 --> 01:00:51.720
molecular matter that sticks to your protein of interest.

1058
01:00:53.740 --> 01:00:57.460
This idea of cooperativity, though, in bifunctional molecules, has really sort

1059
01:00:57.520 --> 01:01:00.988
ofinstigated a desire to screen for

1060
01:01:01.088 --> 01:01:02.488
cooperativity in the first place.

1061
01:01:02.508 --> 01:01:06.448
And so I think more recent approaches are sort of targeting this

1062
01:01:06.508 --> 01:01:10.428
idea that maybe what we should do is use DNA-encoded libraries with

1063
01:01:10.488 --> 01:01:14.008
one partner protein already attached to your ligand with some exposed

1064
01:01:14.048 --> 01:01:16.488
interface that a second partner protein could come engage.

1065
01:01:16.948 --> 01:01:20.488
And by doing that, maybe bias to find cooperative compounds and maybe even

1066
01:01:20.508 --> 01:01:21.368
molecular glues.

1067
01:01:23.168 --> 01:01:26.128
So this idea of ligand first, I think is very interesting.

1068
01:01:26.168 --> 01:01:29.728
It allows you to do a large number of scalable experiments, but it is separated

1069
01:01:29.768 --> 01:01:33.028
from the cellular environment where you actually want your molecule to operate in

1070
01:01:33.048 --> 01:01:36.788
the first place. And I think anyone would understand that there are a

1071
01:01:36.868 --> 01:01:40.768
lot of complexities that go into what has to happen in a cell for an

1072
01:01:40.808 --> 01:01:44.748
induced proximity event to occur, and also how binding can change in the

1073
01:01:44.768 --> 01:01:48.548
cellular environment. So in a solvent of ATP, how does

1074
01:01:49.188 --> 01:01:52.168
engagement with proteins change for small molecule ligands?

1075
01:01:53.548 --> 01:01:57.188
So phenotypic screens or function first screens, I think, are really

1076
01:01:57.228 --> 01:01:57.808
attractive.

1077
01:01:58.768 --> 01:02:02.398
And so they allow you to broadly profile a large number of molecules, figure out if

1078
01:02:02.408 --> 01:02:05.308
they're doing something interesting in the first place, and then chase that

1079
01:02:05.348 --> 01:02:06.508
mechanism down using--

1080
01:02:08.388 --> 01:02:12.288
It used to be really careful biochemical fractionation experiments.

1081
01:02:12.968 --> 01:02:15.608
Now we've lost that ability, and we just do unbiased screens to figure out how

1082
01:02:15.628 --> 01:02:16.068
things work.

1083
01:02:18.588 --> 01:02:22.448
Our ability to do function first is defined

1084
01:02:22.488 --> 01:02:26.108
by, do we have a phenotype that we care about? Often that can be cell death.

1085
01:02:26.168 --> 01:02:29.918
But what about induced proximity, where maybe you want to look at something

1086
01:02:29.988 --> 01:02:31.408
else other than induced cell death?

1087
01:02:31.468 --> 01:02:34.478
You need to expand the range of phenotypes that you can look at through a function

1088
01:02:34.568 --> 01:02:35.328
first mechanism.

1089
01:02:38.888 --> 01:02:42.408
And so in the field of protein degradation, where we're looking for molecules that

1090
01:02:42.428 --> 01:02:46.408
will down-regulate a protein, I think everyone would say we have good strategies

1091
01:02:46.468 --> 01:02:49.488
for looking at that on a small number of compounds.

1092
01:02:50.088 --> 01:02:53.128
Obviously, immunoblots are a fantastic tool.

1093
01:02:53.408 --> 01:02:54.728
That's actually one I ran myself.

1094
01:02:56.688 --> 01:02:59.948
Some people would say that there's a difference between 15% and 28%, as I've shown

1095
01:02:59.968 --> 01:03:01.688
in red. I would say there's no difference.

1096
01:03:01.828 --> 01:03:05.588
I would say there's almost no difference between 50% and 20% or

1097
01:03:05.628 --> 01:03:09.138
10%. And that's because the immunoblot is obviously a great

1098
01:03:09.168 --> 01:03:10.988
tool, but it's a

1099
01:03:12.068 --> 01:03:13.148
somewhat subjective tool.

1100
01:03:14.188 --> 01:03:16.628
Flow cytometry is really exciting, right?

1101
01:03:16.688 --> 01:03:20.148
It allows us to look at the single molecule level about how something might be

1102
01:03:20.188 --> 01:03:23.528
changing. So you fuse your protein of interest to a fluorescent reporter, and you

1103
01:03:23.568 --> 01:03:27.308
look for changes in abundance. And you can do that somewhat scalably

1104
01:03:27.388 --> 01:03:31.368
across single cells, although it starts to have diminished returns when you think

1105
01:03:31.428 --> 01:03:34.628
about trying to scale it up. Then proteomics is fantastic.

1106
01:03:34.688 --> 01:03:38.588
It gives us a huge snapshot of a number of different abundance changes that are

1107
01:03:38.608 --> 01:03:40.788
happening in cells, a function of a molecule treatment.

1108
01:03:41.368 --> 01:03:45.268
The sensitivity might be no better than what a western blot might be,

1109
01:03:45.648 --> 01:03:48.328
but allows us to look at a larger swath of proteins. Okay?

1110
01:03:49.068 --> 01:03:52.848
I would say all of these are limited in their ability to look at molecules

1111
01:03:53.148 --> 01:03:55.788
and other phenotypes at scale. So,

1112
01:03:57.668 --> 01:04:01.438
no one's going to run 10,000 western blots in triplicate probably to do a

1113
01:04:01.468 --> 01:04:05.428
high-throughput screen. And if you are, please talk to me, because we

1114
01:04:05.468 --> 01:04:06.028
can fix that.

1115
01:04:08.068 --> 01:04:11.268
Flow cytometry and high-throughput flow cytometry has really emerged as something

1116
01:04:11.288 --> 01:04:14.468
that's quite exciting. But then you still have a statistical significance problem.

1117
01:04:15.728 --> 01:04:19.548
As you go to high throughput and you try to go faster for flow cytometry, you start

1118
01:04:19.568 --> 01:04:22.348
to lose statistical significance for what you can draw from any small molecule

1119
01:04:22.428 --> 01:04:25.908
screen. So you start to lose that sensitivity that makes flow cytometry so

1120
01:04:25.948 --> 01:04:27.148
attractive in the first place.

1121
01:04:28.788 --> 01:04:32.468
And then proteomics, while you might be able to buy yourself a farm of mass

1122
01:04:32.508 --> 01:04:36.108
spectrometers and be operating them continuously for several years at a time,

1123
01:04:36.828 --> 01:04:40.728
it's just hard to screen a huge number of molecules to get statistical power

1124
01:04:40.808 --> 01:04:43.408
to say that small changes are something that you can say for real.

1125
01:04:44.677 --> 01:04:48.348
And so what my lab is really excited by is this idea that maybe we should think

1126
01:04:48.408 --> 01:04:52.328
about how to develop more scalable technologies for finding molecules or profiling

1127
01:04:52.348 --> 01:04:56.288
entire biological pathways. And so where I would say scalable technologies are

1128
01:04:56.308 --> 01:05:00.138
really needed is in this high-throughput screening of small molecule libraries

1129
01:05:00.168 --> 01:05:03.168
to find interesting phenotypes like protein degradation or other induced

1130
01:05:03.188 --> 01:05:06.388
proximities-driven approaches.

1131
01:05:08.068 --> 01:05:11.188
The corollary of that is in the small molecule space, you want to find molecules.

1132
01:05:11.528 --> 01:05:15.008
In the genetic mapping space, rather than running a single CRISPR screen to

1133
01:05:15.048 --> 01:05:18.448
identify the regulator of one protein, wouldn't it be powerful if we could run

1134
01:05:18.568 --> 01:05:22.428
screens of CRISPR screens to map an entire pathway or an entire family of proteins

1135
01:05:22.508 --> 01:05:23.868
that stabilize or destabilize?

1136
01:05:24.768 --> 01:05:28.528
And so this really begs the question, how can we observe changes in the proteome at

1137
01:05:28.628 --> 01:05:32.188
scale to drive molecule discovery and biological discovery?

1138
01:05:32.708 --> 01:05:36.048
And so I'll talk a little bit about the efforts towards how we can maybe build a

1139
01:05:36.108 --> 01:05:40.068
new way to think about trying to find new molecules that change protein

1140
01:05:40.108 --> 01:05:40.528
levels.

1141
01:05:42.848 --> 01:05:43.308
Okay, so

1142
01:05:44.768 --> 01:05:48.368
there's a large number of ways that you could profile protein stabilization

1143
01:05:48.408 --> 01:05:52.368
changes. We wanted to take a step back and ask if you could design from scratch an

1144
01:05:52.448 --> 01:05:56.168
assay that would allow you to profile proteins at scale with high

1145
01:05:56.228 --> 01:05:59.608
sensitivity, what would that look like? And so here's what we came up with.

1146
01:06:00.128 --> 01:06:03.328
One is that it would allow you to differentiate cell death and viability.

1147
01:06:03.528 --> 01:06:06.528
So having it in live cells is really advantageous because you can tell if something

1148
01:06:06.548 --> 01:06:07.328
is toxic or not.

1149
01:06:08.368 --> 01:06:11.308
You want to be able to detect realistic of degradations of a protein of interest.

1150
01:06:11.388 --> 01:06:15.208
So I think everyone's dream is from a screen finding a molecule that degrades your

1151
01:06:15.228 --> 01:06:19.108
protein 90+%. The reality of that is for challenging targets,

1152
01:06:19.948 --> 01:06:21.167
that's probably going to be pretty hard.

1153
01:06:21.608 --> 01:06:24.378
So you want to detect something that you can actually do med chem on.

1154
01:06:24.798 --> 01:06:26.888
And as a good starting point, you want to find those hits.

1155
01:06:26.908 --> 01:06:30.248
So I would say that trying to find degraders that operate within the 10% to 50%

1156
01:06:30.288 --> 01:06:31.628
window is actually the challenge.

1157
01:06:32.868 --> 01:06:36.548
You want your signal to be robust, right? So you want to minimize false positives.

1158
01:06:36.588 --> 01:06:39.788
And for us, this really means you want to create signal rather than destroy signal.

1159
01:06:40.168 --> 01:06:42.148
So you need to have this inversion, where if you're looking at protein

1160
01:06:42.188 --> 01:06:45.888
destabilization, you need to somehow convert that into increase of

1161
01:06:45.928 --> 01:06:46.288
something.

1162
01:06:47.968 --> 01:06:50.608
You want to be able to do this across many hundreds of proteins.

1163
01:06:50.648 --> 01:06:52.838
Maybe even many hundreds of proteins simultaneously.

1164
01:06:54.368 --> 01:06:56.708
And then finally, you want it to be relatively mechanistically agnostic.

1165
01:06:57.008 --> 01:07:00.828
You don't necessarily care about how your protein is being degraded sometimes, just

1166
01:07:00.848 --> 01:07:04.668
that it is being degraded and being degraded selectively.So

1167
01:07:05.008 --> 01:07:08.288
we put all these ideas together, and obviously you want to do this from many, many

1168
01:07:08.328 --> 01:07:11.928
molecules at once And we thought, well, how does

1169
01:07:12.528 --> 01:07:15.348
nature actually sense protein degradation in the first place?

1170
01:07:16.088 --> 01:07:19.678
So nature's developed transcription as a way to read out destabilization of

1171
01:07:19.688 --> 01:07:23.628
proteins Okay? So very famously, this molecular switch,

1172
01:07:24.028 --> 01:07:27.968
where upon some stimulus, IKB alpha is degraded and leads

1173
01:07:28.008 --> 01:07:31.998
to NF-kappa B initiating transcriptional responses, is a really powerful

1174
01:07:32.028 --> 01:07:35.818
example of that. And in the DNA damage space, we observe this

1175
01:07:35.848 --> 01:07:37.348
again, where upon DNA damage,

1176
01:07:38.288 --> 01:07:42.188
MDM2 can be degraded, releasing p53 to then turn on DNA damage

1177
01:07:42.228 --> 01:07:46.048
response pathways. And so nature uses transcription to read out

1178
01:07:46.058 --> 01:07:46.978
protein degradation.

1179
01:07:48.588 --> 01:07:51.858
Can we do that synthetically? Can we build transcriptional response systems that

1180
01:07:51.888 --> 01:07:55.388
allow us to profile, and profile very sensitively, protein degradation?

1181
01:07:56.008 --> 01:07:59.338
And so what we came up with is this idea of ratiometric transcriptional activation,

1182
01:07:59.848 --> 01:08:03.028
where you fuse your protein of interest to an inhibitor of a transcription factor,

1183
01:08:03.808 --> 01:08:06.808
and then you place that in cells with a transcription factor.

1184
01:08:07.338 --> 01:08:10.768
And upon degradation of that inhibitor, which is fused to your protein of interest,

1185
01:08:11.128 --> 01:08:13.908
you release that transcription factor to turn on any gene you program.

1186
01:08:14.328 --> 01:08:17.788
So you can create an amplified readout in live cells using

1187
01:08:17.848 --> 01:08:21.468
fluorescence, cell survival, or even RNA barcode production

1188
01:08:21.888 --> 01:08:25.568
to create something that is scalable, highly sensitive, and very multiplexable.

1189
01:08:26.928 --> 01:08:29.588
And so what this relies on is our ability to program cells.

1190
01:08:29.628 --> 01:08:33.518
It relies on our ability to encode in cells this inhibitor, a transcription

1191
01:08:33.608 --> 01:08:37.068
factor, and then to use molecules to read out

1192
01:08:37.568 --> 01:08:39.168
production of our signal of interest.

1193
01:08:40.608 --> 01:08:41.949
And so we built a few test cases,

1194
01:08:43.248 --> 01:08:47.188
and what we saw in this test case where we used FKBP-12, F36B

1195
01:08:47.248 --> 01:08:51.029
as a model protein using dTag molecules as a nice degrader control,

1196
01:08:51.568 --> 01:08:55.239
is that you can directly observe production of GFP as a function of protein

1197
01:08:55.239 --> 01:08:55.808
degradation.

1198
01:08:57.428 --> 01:09:01.398
This is a polyclonal cell line. So we encode all of these different components into

1199
01:09:01.409 --> 01:09:04.538
a cell, and it's somewhat random. Different copy numbers of the different

1200
01:09:04.548 --> 01:09:06.869
components create this polyclonal cell line.

1201
01:09:06.909 --> 01:09:09.529
But what you can see is something that is quite good.

1202
01:09:09.588 --> 01:09:12.688
You now have this inversion of response, where upon protein degradation, you see

1203
01:09:12.728 --> 01:09:13.588
increase of GFP.

1204
01:09:15.108 --> 01:09:16.288
Can we tune it?

1205
01:09:17.248 --> 01:09:20.968
We go in and we do single-cell sorting at different concentrations of our molecule

1206
01:09:20.989 --> 01:09:23.168
to identify cells that are more and less sensitive.

1207
01:09:23.668 --> 01:09:27.489
And what this allows us to do is basically to shift the EC50 profile of any clonal

1208
01:09:27.508 --> 01:09:31.398
cell line to be extremely sensitive or to be relatively insensitive, depending

1209
01:09:31.428 --> 01:09:33.888
on what level of degradation you want to detect.

1210
01:09:33.928 --> 01:09:37.869
So on one side, we can go all the way to 160 picomolar for one EC50

1211
01:09:37.888 --> 01:09:41.648
value, and then we shift that about two orders of magnitude to a higher EC50

1212
01:09:41.668 --> 01:09:45.388
value. And what these EC50 values translate to is how sensitive can you

1213
01:09:45.409 --> 01:09:46.489
detect protein degradation.

1214
01:09:47.348 --> 01:09:51.268
At EC50, 160 picomolar, we're detecting 10% protein

1215
01:09:51.329 --> 01:09:55.128
degradation. At EC50, 13 nanomolar, we're

1216
01:09:55.148 --> 01:09:58.808
